<TITLE> Dhaka to seek help halting terror funds </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, March 27 (bdnews24.com)Dhaka will talk to friendly states on coordinated efforts to halt terror funds, said the state minister for home on Friday. "We have to tackle militancy and terrorism by joining hands with others who believe in cooperation," Tanjim Ahmed told reporters at Zia International Airport before his departure for the US. The minister was on his way to attend the 15th Annual Pacific Special Command Programme in Hawaii from March 29-April 3 with participants from 20 countries. The state minister, who leads a three-member delegation, said, "The conference will mainly discuss counter terrorism strategies." "On ways to combat militancy and terrorism locally and internationally, with special focus on multi-state coordinated efforts." "The issue of forming an international taskforce for effectively fighting terrorism will also be looked into." Tanjim said he would raise Bangladesh's security concerns at the conference. Asked in what areas Bangladesh would seek international assistance against terrorism, the state minister said, "As we would extend support to others who need it, we may also seek assistance in times of need." Asked why British citizen Faisal Mostafa, alleged to have links to the recent arms haul at a Bhola madrasa, has not been named an accused in the related cases, Tanjim said, "We'll take necessary steps against all when the occasion warrants it, irrespective of citizenship or guise." "Our intelligence agencies are watching and monitoring," said the minister. bdnews
